Higgs' boson explored
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused legitimate awakening last summer.
There is a view that this boson is involved in the mechanism that is responsible for all matter in the universe.
And further, it is the last particle, the existence of which is predicted by a standard model - our best or "the least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - which, however, has not yet been empirically observed.
However, there is no hundred percent certainty among physicists that it is the Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have a completely new particle available, which is very similar to the Higgs boson, as predicted by the standard model.
The new data published this week during the Great Physical Congress in Kyoto rather confirms it, but we still lack all the data to be absolutely sure.
However, let’s assume that it’s the Higgs boson, as the risk of error seems small, and let’s see what’s actually going on.
In this world, there is an unquestionable law that states that two things cannot happen at the same time at the same place.
This rule cannot be overlooked - and do not try too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also applies a similar law: Paul's excretion principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" approximately creates some of their properties.
It also divides the physical particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find organized citizens, or fermions, who obey Paul's principle.
And at the other end the bosons are moving, underlying anarchists, who don’t value anything at all – definitely not this principle, which means they can calmly be in the same place at the same time.
Furthermore, these bosons are divided into two groups according to the device (by the way, absolutely amazing), which is The Particle Adventure, in the Berkeley laboratories: the mesons that we leave here unnoticed, and the "power particles", which spread great natural forces and with which the Higgs boson is probably somehow associated.
However, it must be said that these bosons are not as exotic animals as it could be thought.
If you read this article, it’s thanks to a boson with an unusual banality: a photon, or “light particles”, which is the “bearer” of electromagnetic power.
In fact, when the particles with electric charge accelerate or change their direction, they “interrupt” the electromagnetic field in this particular place, like the slurry thrown into the waterfall.
From this "interruption" an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) is created and this wave is nothing but a photon - and thus one of the bosons, "powerholders".
More stable field
It’s also with the Higgs boson, just with the difference that it’s necessary to “interrupt” another field, the Higgs field, to make this boson appear.
This Higgs field is much more, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to very high energy values, just like the frozen level of the aquarium, that only a lot of large balvan will eat.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such an enormous part accelerator as a accelerator in the CERN laboratory - a large hadron accelerator with friendly bonds is a circle with a circle of 27 km! - to be possible to develop such energy.
Analogies with the electromagnetic field are again suitable for us to clarify the relationship between Higgs and matter.
With the electromagnetic field, neither all particles nor all materials react.
Some, for example, magnets, do so, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold on its own on the refrigerator.
And the same way, with the Higgs field, not all particles react: those that do so have a certain matter, while others (such as a photon, let’s look at it) don’t have it.
And Mrs. Novakova asks what all these researches are, what will they bring to us?
From the point of view of science, it is confirming the validity of the standard model (SM), which allows physicists to undergo the investigation of any disconformity between observation and predictions of the SM.
In addition, a few physicists literally wish to find them, because the smallest difference could open the space of "new physics" and fix some gap in the model.
It is to be noted that the model has so far enormous shortcomings, does not bring any clarification of gravity (ouha!) or dark matter, which forms approximately 80% of space matter ( again ouha!).
However, CERN has not yet discovered such contradictions.
Reactions
The responses of these research in Mr. and Mrs. Novakovsky’s daily life can only be predicted very hard, but it would be a mistake to believe that it will not be any.
Look: at the beginning of the 1960s, the pioneers of the Bell laboratory had no idea of the revolution that their work would trigger.
They predicted scientific use, but nothing more.
Physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first permanent laser rays (the previous rays were pulse) in 1962, I have already said it - the laser was initially considered such a "laboratory toy".
Just imagine it...
In addition, the application can also come from all the tools that surround the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle created a small light sensor in 1969 during his work focused on optics.
This sensor, although it was not so planned by Boyle at first, now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras in the world and won him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that activities around LHC necessarily have to change our lives, but it means that one really never knows...
