“Thro your life, you’re learning that men’s urine stands,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois facility.
Return to the child’s stage is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
“It depends on the ability of the person,” whether the return will be accepted, says the psychologist.
According to a number of people engaged in palliative care, the crucial moments take place in the core of such a return.
Patients who go home with Victor-Gadbois palliative care all suffer from cancer.
Their forecast is a maximum of three months of life.
At this stage, the team of doctors and nurses who take care of them does not provide them with so-called "therapeutic" care.
In the case of Mrs. A., 89 years of age, the worst fear is to die "on an uprising with full consciousness".
But the illness allowed me to discover my children.
“I have good children,” he added.
"I don't have any desire in life anymore," she says, and then she allows us to put her on a respiratory device.
However, he is still looking forward to the last visit of his son from Italy in the following days.
In the house of Victor-Gadbois, in collaboration with a group of volunteers, body care is provided with the help of nutrition.
This is how palliative care appears, which occurs when nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, one bed palliative care per 11,700 inhabitants.
This is very little if we realize that we all die once.
Here life continues in optimal conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors at home.
Whether it is a level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When a person dies, you can give him, for example, a brandy douch or pepsi, according to the taste.
Diabetics no longer need to keep their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
They brought a beer to Mr. X, who died later in the night.
This morning, his son will drink beer in honor of the deceased father.
“We’re helping patients as well as their loved ones,” says Nathalie Savard, Director of the Care Service.
In the house of Victor-Gadbois, the days go one after the other, but they don’t resemble each other.
In addition to a thirty-nine-year-old man, who is delighted by the last meeting with his family thoroughly grounded on his wings while drinking for his honor, a tragically thirty-six-year-old man, surrounded by his parents, his wife and two little children, dies after he has tried all the possibilities to survive.
“For six months there are always three to five beds that are intended for people with cancer under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who come to Victor-Gadbois home come from their homes and 47% from hospitals.
Problems with access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. to care that is intended to relieve suffering as soon as the sick reaches the final phase of his life, whether it is at home, in the hospital or in the care house.
And several organizations, such as the home Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Home Palliative Treatment of the Grand Montréal Region, are more or less exclusively specialized in the care provided to oncological patients.
And this substantial lack of medical care in Quebec leads to the fact that a number of doctors specializing in palliative care are worried about the adoption of the law on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto is in circulation signed by top leaders in palliative therapy, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, in which they demonstrate their disagreement with such initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not efficient enough to ensure that all people have access to high-quality palliative care before euthanasia can be accepted.
As she says, she recently experienced a patient who spent 14 days on emergency in enormous pain, without anyone taking the necessary steps to relieve her.
It is concerned that patients will not ask for death because they are not given adequate care.
And at the same time, a number of oncologists take care of their patients until the last few minutes regardless of the negative forecast.
Hélène Richard's hopes for survival were already minimal when she left the challenging chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I’m ending treatment, she replied that she’s regret that I’m ceasing to fight, she tells us.
She told me that it was over!
There is no all-power care.
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of the sick who wish to die thank their healing doctors for not fulfilling their wishes when the palliative pipe team relieved their pain.
But it must be said that palliative care is definitely not all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, Director of Palliative Care in the Company for Home Palliative Care in the Grand Montréal Region, patients prevent pain treatment in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often use palliative sedatives, which succeed the patient up to the moment of swelling, whether it’s striking or whether the sedatives are given permanently.
We cannot pretend that we do not perceive this part of suffering.
The patient, whom we don’t get rid of the pain, will have increasingly the possibility of access to palliative sedatives.
Patients who are not given a sedative always say the same: “I want to die.”
But that doesn’t always necessarily mean “I want you to give me euthanasia,” rather it means “I want you to get rid of my pain.”
