Poland’s journey to space began far earlier.
The Polish enthusiasts were dedicated to the flights to space before World War II; but they did not always encounter understanding.
I will remember, for example, A. Sternfeld's lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, who on 6 December 1933 presented the ideas from his pioneering work The Entry into Cosmonautika.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold and after years Sternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934 he was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for the Entry in Space.
Remembered Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-famous promoter of cosmonautics and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the reverse side of the moon was named by his name.
In 1925, a railroad was built in Poland, which was intended to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the project is unknown and the details of the project are not known.
It is not even clear whether the missile was to be used to launch the drain or to block it.
The information about this plot is only known from the time press.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery has begun to occupy with missiles.
The research was carried out by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfk and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegim.
From the materials preserved it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the research was interrupted.
In 1937, the design of a photoelectric fighter missile appeared in the professional press, designed by the engineer Rohoziński, and the following year the work of the Rocket - torpedo airzna and Rocketbomba lotnicza was published by the author of Leliwy-Krzywoblockého.
Both projects were designed for military use of missile engines.
Just before the war, the temporary scientific advisory committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was dedicated to all projects of military use of missile technology, which coordinated all the work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity its activity ended the beginning of the war.
Other works dedicated to space science appear in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, the company is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the magazine Problems, which contains four more comprehensive articles dedicated to astronomy.
In one of them, by Prof. M. Subotowitz, it is proposed to create a society that will engage in cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already broken down, and it was clear that space research was a prospective field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronomical Society (PTA) has been trying to join the International Astronomical Federation (founded in 1951) and in the autumn, the PTA has become a regular member.
And the following year, the first Chairman of the PTA Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959) became the Vice Chairman of the International Astronaut Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has contributed significantly to the development of the very successful meteorological missile RM (Meteorological Rocket), which became the first Polish missile to conduct scientific research.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The 1,800-meter missile was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of RM-1A was built and in the summer of 1959 a two-step RM-2 missile test was launched in the Bledov Desert.
The missile was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of development had already been able to real scientific work - the RM-34 was to have a reach of up to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the height wind.
However, in 1962, further development was suspended.
The successor of the first RM rocket was the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was conceived as a two-step, its total length was 510 cm and the start weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (marked Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of space for scientific devices.
The Meteor-1A was available space of 0.4 liters, the Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and the Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum access for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 was developed at the Aeronautical Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 missile had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful load of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
The following versions of Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
