The South American Summit ends and the Lima Declaration has not been published
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) held in Peru today ended without the release of the Lima Declaration, which was announced and allegedly signed by seven presidential presidents.
Efe has repeatedly tried to gain access to the document signed at the sixth meeting of the UNASUR heads of states and governments, but representatives of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidential Office, who initially decided that the document will be published after the summit ended, said it would be published later on the website of the Peruvian government.
The content was published by Peruvian President Ollanta Humala in a few short press statements.
Journalists had limited access to information throughout the summit.
During the talks, a video from the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room without a sound with the message "confidential meeting, the transmission of the sound was prevented".
A small amount of information that the journalists had available was provided by the press spokesmen of some governments who were present to the talks, but not by the Peruvian spokesmen.
The only document published during the talks was the list of participating presidents, which caused the wrath of hundreds of journalists from different national and international media who asked for more information.
Later, the Peruvian presidential office sent to the media an e-mail with a “final statement” from the summit, but it’s just a statement by President Humala, not an official document that the summit closed.
Last October, Peru hosted the third Summit of South American and Arab Countries (America del Sur-Países Árabes, ASPA) and even at this occasion the initially promised Declaration of Lima was not published, although the press was demanding.
On the official website of the ASPA it can be found that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities strived to ensure broadcasting for all journalists, but completely prevented the supply of information.
The summit ended, among other things, with a joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt the judgment of the Hague Court, which addresses the border dispute between the two countries.
Peru's President Ollanta Humala and Chile's President Sebastián Piñera met during a regional meeting and confirmed that they will respect the decision of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which will begin on Monday by hearing the defence speech of both sides to discuss the dispute that launched Lima against Santiago.
“We will make and execute a judgment that will resolve the dispute that we are discussing today at this international court,” President Humala said along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is, and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful settlement of disputes, conventions and international courts," Piñera added and greeted President Humal with a hand pressure at the flags of both countries.
