Fabrizi was 21 years old when his test result was confirmed: HIV positive.
"It was as if a flash hit me," he tells in remembrance of the moment of truth that the doctor tried to "a little relieve", but obviously without success.
The boy hidden it from his family.
He decided to take his illness himself on his beds and began informing about it. And that with such a commitment that he had already celebrated his 43th birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest HIV patients at the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), to which he arrived in 1994 after several battles with the disease.
Fabrizio has lived with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) since the age of 22, which was something unimaginable in the early 1990s, when there was a lot of doubt, little treatment options and greater stigma.
At that time, even the director of the clinic of the Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) didn’t say goodbye to him, “because he had a cut wound.”
AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it is possible to survive and live fully with this syndrome.
However, there are a lot of people who don’t know about their disease and come only when the virus has caused damage to the body and transmitted the immune system, and then become victims of random infections.
31 years since AIDS appeared in the world, or at least since the first documented cases, “is a great success that the lifetime of a patient who starts treatment in a timely and appropriate way is completely the same as in healthy people,” said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital in Guadalajara with the fact that this information was confirmed in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectologist and HIV/AIDS specialist Andrade Villanueva explained that scientists have come to the conclusion that since 2008 AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the duration of survival and full life depends on the degree of immune affection of the patients who are diagnosed with the disease, with better on those who do not take drugs: people with 200 CD4 cells can live up to 30 years and people with 500 CD4 cells up to 50 years.
Simply said, this means that the person who is diagnosed with HIV at the age of 25 can, according to these findings, "when followed treatment, live without problems up to 75 years," the doctor explained in an interview.
To emphasize this progress, it is advisable to remind that the average lifetime of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although the mortality rate has decreased significantly in recent years, and in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died from AIDS has decreased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (the year of the UN Joint Programme for HIV/AIDS – UNAIDS), it is also true that since the discovery of AIDS, according to national statistics, 60 percent of patients have died.
Only in the state of Jalisco, 255 people died in 2011 and until this year’s May so far 187. however, since 2005, universal access to antiretrovirus drugs has been secured.
Why do people continue to die from the consequences of the disease?
"It seems to me that the problem is not in the possibilities of access to treatment.
This is what happens in the hospital.
The problem is that patients come in a very advanced stage because they don’t know the state of the infection, i.e. in the late stage of the disease.”
He adds a convincing figure: "Nine out of ten patients come when some associated infection is already manifested.The only thing we need to do to be able to more influence the overall mortality is to diagnose the disease earlier, and therefore it is necessary to offer tests on a large scale to detect the disease to all the people who ask for them."
In his proposal, he agrees with specialists and officials from the State Council for AIDS prevention in the state of Jalisco and directly with patients like Fabrizio, who came to make tests to a private laboratory just because it was done by his friend, and despite his low age he has already propelled AIDS and also suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a tumor disease that is one of the usual complications.
“Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they’re going to die, and they don’t want to know anything else.
“If I’m going to die, I’m better doing it three times a week,” they say, but that’s not my case.
The change was to better, I eat it healthy, I exercise, I take medications.”
Until now, his parents only know that he was suffering from cancer.
I live a normal life like everyone else.
I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I lead an active sexual life, but responsibly, I pay attention to myself and the other person,” says Fabrizio, who received the call to share his experience with the journal MILENIO JALISCO, to motivate those who are afraid with his testimony today as part of World AIDS Day.
"Let them do tests. if they risk, let them know as soon as possible if they are HIV-positive, it's better. and if they've already been diagnosed, let them realize that they can live like anyone else when they're responsible."
This message summarizes the motto of the fight against AIDS in this year 2012.
Condoms behind the pult
There is a big gap between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara journalist who finds information about HIV.
The biggest gap is in prevention.
“In places dedicated to this task, the distribution of preservatives has actually increased, before they gave us one or two, today they give us packages and a hundred preservatives, which is very good, but still there are people who do not have access to preservatives,” he said.
Among the most susceptible to new diseases are adolescents.
