Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Basketball world runner Héctor "Hetin" Reyes has been associated with this hall sport for more than 60 years and has traveled the whole world thanks to it.
Few people in Puerto Rico have so many memories of the history of local basketball as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes has.
Before he was hit by a stroke on a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was burned into this sport for more than 60 years, whether as a player of younger categories, player of the National Basketball League BSN, owner and coach of the team Vaqueros de Bayamón in the National Basketball League, or president of the Portoric Basketball Federation.
“I’ve played a lot of roles throughout my life in basketball, including several at the same time, as when I was the president of the BSN National League in the 1990s, the chief executive of the national team and the chairman of the federation,” Reyes recalled when he visited the journalists of Primera Hora at his home in Bayamón, where he has lived for more than 50 years with Isabel, his faithful wife.
“Basketball was my life.”
Reyes does not exaggerate.
The walls of his house, which are almost all decorated with photos and reminder items from his long career, prove that.
Bayamon in the Heart
With the greatest motivation of all the guards are those that remind him of his work in Los Vaqueros from the mid-50s, where he was a player until 1982, when he also celebrated 15 years as co-owners or team owners.
“It was my best years, the one I’ve most, because I’ve had the opportunity to take part in eight championships with Los Vaqueros since 1967, whether as a owner, co-owners, or coach.
It was a number of successful years, including five championships held between 1971 and 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one championship - in 1981, when Jerome Mincy debuted in BSN.
Then the team took over "Cuco" Ortiz, who was an excellent leader," Reyes said.
“I remember that Gene Bartow, who was here before as a coach and at that time worked at the University of Alabama in Birmingham, told me, ‘I have a two-meter player for you.
Do you want him?”
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players that Puerto Rico ever had.
Bartow then recommended me the player Raymond Gausse, who became a team member and one of our best shooters.
I remember he said that if Mincy brings a win to Bayamon in the championship, Gausse will then contribute to the next.”
The championship, when for the team los Vaqueros played Gausse, was pleased, but only on a distance, since in 1988 he already performed the position of president of the basketball federation.
At that time, he wanted to dedicate himself fully to his functions and enjoy Mincy's position in the national team.
“I remember the first time we defeated the United States at the qualifying Olympics in Mexico in 1989.
Then the World Cup came in 1990, where we ended the quarter, but we had to have a bronze without the Canadian judge who allowed us to repeat the final throwing,” Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you’ve ever seen?
He is among the best, as well as the one who defeated Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favourite was the national team at the 1991 Pan-American Games in Cuba, when we won the gold and scratched the U.S. team, which was quite similar to the one that blown us bronze at the World Cup.
This team had not only Mincy, Gausse, Ramona Rivase, Fica Lopez and "Piculina" (Ortiz), but also there were young people (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers of León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who couldn't be in the team in 1990 due to knee injury.
The team that didn’t have the perfect composition, but was able to win us the gold medal and bring great joy, was the team from the Olympic qualification in 1995 in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players on the list, such as "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and junior player Rolando Hourruitiner, who replaced players excluded because of the match at the Pan-American Games in Mar de Plata, we, despite all the forecasts, won gold.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
It was without any doubt Piculin Ortiz.
His figures from international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has achieved at this level such results as Piculin.
Not to mention his performance in the different leagues where he played.
Who was the best Portoric coach?
This is very difficult.
We had a very good generation, which includes Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau and Armandito Torres.
I like the work of Leo Arilla.
What is your biggest success in the Federation?
That I was part of the most famous era of the national team between 1988 and 1995 and that at the beginning of the 90s the national league BSN had up to 17 teams in one season.
What did you not prove?
There were things I wanted to introduce, such as the division of youth categories by regions.
For example, the Ponce guys would only play in their area and compete with teams from other corners of the island only in national play-offs.
Now kids travel a lot and play too many matches, which is not necessary.
I also see the contribution in mandatory certificates and courses for coaches, assistants of arbitrators and arbitrators.
That pleases me.
What are you engaged in now?
I most listen to music, watch YouTube videos with music from my time, enjoy my grandchildren and sometimes go to basketball matches.
And of course I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel, who was always on my side.
Actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, born on 21 September 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas, is worldly famous for the main role of John Rosse Ewing, better known as "J.R." in the television series Dallas, in which he embodies a man who acted carelessly and was malicious and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role of drunk oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series Dallas became a symbol of hunger in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned as J.R. this year in the new Dallas series, died according to a family official announcement provided to the Associated Press by Dallas production company Warner Bros., on Friday afternoon from complications associated with cancer.
“Larry returned to his beloved hometown Dallas, where he again played the iconic role he liked most,” his family said.
Larry's family and his closest friends were with him in Dallas on Thanksgiving Day.
"Linda Gray, who was the representative of his wife in the original and new series, was with Hagman at the moment he died in the Dallas hospital," said her agent Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to everyone he knew.
He was creative, generous, fun, kind, kind and talented, and I will miss him very much.
He was unique and lived his life fully,” Linda Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and he himself admitted that he drank a lot for years.
In 1995 he was found a malignant tumor on his liver and Hagman was transplanted.
Years before the Dallas series was broadcast, Hagman was famous on television as a decent guy in the light comedy I Dream of Jeannie broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
Here he played the character of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive girl (Jina) played by Barbara Eden, and takes her home to live together.
He was also protagonist in two comedies that were broadcast shortly, The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His performance in the films included roles that were well-accepted by criticism: The Group, Harry and Tonto and Primary Colors.
But it was Hangman's masterpiece in the form of an incredibly repugnant J.R., who led him to the star peak.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters around them was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional slogan "Who Shot Jayara?", which had to raise expectations about the work full of emotions, when Hangman's character is almost murdered, caused not only an enormous number of speculations from viewers around the world, but also the risk of millions of dollars in tax offices.
This also helped this work to reach a record in tracking.
The November 1980 episode, in which the answer was revealed, watched an average of 41 million TV viewers. Dallas became the second most watched entertainment show in history after the completion of the 1983 MASH series, which watched 50 million viewers.
At J.R. he was shot by his cousin Kristin (who played Mary Crosby).
Kristin and J.R. were pregnant and he threatened to call her a prostitute if she did not leave the city.
Hagman played Ewing, an untouched jealous with a charismatic smile: a lazy entrepreneur and unfaithful husband who sought to make his wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), who was an alcoholic, closed into the hospital.
"I know what I want to have J.R. on the tomb stone," Hagman said in 1988.
It should be there: "Here lies the honorary citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only thing he failed.
Victoria Principal, who played in the original series, remembered Hagman on Friday as someone who was "beautiful on the plate and outside."
It is unforgettable and irreplaceable for millions of fans in the world and in the hearts of us all who had the luck to know and love him.
Ten pieces of the new Dallas series was broadcast by TNT a few months ago with great success.
"The filming of five parts of the second series has already been completed and the sixth is just rounded," the television station.
Immediately after Hangman's death, there was no statement from Warner or TNT on how the series will continue.
A native of Fort Worth in Texas was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who glowed in classical works such as South Pacific and Peter Pan musicals.
Mary Martin was a very young girl when in 1931 she gave birth to Larry, whose father was her husband, the lawyer Ben Hagman.
In the early 1950s, Larry tried his luck on the theater scenes in New York and then served in the British Air Force between 1952 and 1956.
There he met the young Swedish designer Maj Axelsson, with whom he married.
The married couple had two children, Prestona and Heidi, and for a long time they lived in the California city of Malibu, where many celebrity stayed.
In 2001 he published his autobiographical book Hello Darlin: Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life.
"I didn't have anything that I knew could hurt someone or hurt him somehow," he told Press Association.
After a liver transplant, he began to promote organ donation and worked as a volunteer in a hospital where he helped scary patients.
“I advise them, I give them courage, I meet them when they go to surgery and then,” he said in 1996.
I try to give them comfort in the sense of "Don't worry, it will be a bit unpleasant for a moment, but you'll be healthy."
He was also an activist in the fight against smoking and participated in various campaigns.
