Every week students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria and global warming.
When Professor of Religion Stuart Charmé decided that this semester would make a course about the end of the world, he knew it was an irresistible attraction: The end of the "long number" of the May calendar, which is scheduled to come on December 21, has been captured by many people as proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea what was waiting for him in the next few months: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, a budget gap that some call "the debt Armageddon", and the growing conflict into which Israel is drawn, the place where, according to Christians theorizing the end of the world, the Apocalypse begins.
"I didn't realize that this would be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told Rutgers University students this week in Camden, New Jersey.
When one discovers what is happening in the world today, as if we had 30 days left, it’s really a good time.
And remember that bad means good for apocalyptic thinking.
And it’s not the only professor offering courses about the “end of the world” in this semester, which is theoretically the last in history.
At the University of Temple, the professional assistant Barry Vacker organizes the course "Middles, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria and global warming.
“We’re understanding why these thoughts are expanding over time,” he says, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that govern certain human behavior.
For example, if the nuclear material gets into the hands of the terrorists, a war may begin.
This month, students analyze movies with apocalyptic topics and explore how they differ from real-life examples.
"I tried to inform students about what is possible, likely, credible and impossible," says Vacker.
